title: E3D V5/V6 FAN DUCT FOR FLSUN DELTA KOSSEL

description.text:
Después de mucho pelear con distintas toberas de ventilación, y sin buenos resultados he decidido partir de 0 y he hecho una pieza para resolver de un golpe dos cosas. De una parte, ganar algo de diametro máximo de impresión, y de otra con un solo ventilador efectivo ventilar el disipador y la extrusión para el tema de los puentes y voladizos.
Este sistema se acopla al soporte que tiene la impresora FLSUN, y que por defecto atornilla ahí el único ventilador (haciendo perder 2 cm de diámetro).
He usado los mismos tornillos M3 de cabeza Allen, pero colocando unos de cabeza plana se podrá ganar aun más diámetro.
Esta compuesto por dos piezas que se atorillan con los mismos tornillos del ventilador de 40 mm.
Lo he probado y el resultado es muy bueno.

Delta Kossel FLSN

comments.text:
Muchas gracias! La idea que tenia era usar un solo ventilador (el que viene en el kit) para de una parte refrigerar el disipador del calefactor y de otra hacer un blower para el secado del PLA (En especial en los voladizos).
De momento funciona, pero tal vez tengas razón. Un saludo!

comments.text: yo también uso solo el ventilador del kit, y como te dije antes, tu idea es muy buena (refrigeras y ahorras espacio) pero el aire que escapa por la parte de arriba enfria un poco el bloque calefactor, lo que hace trabajar mas la electronica, si extruyes una especie de tobera hasta donde acaba el disipador evitaría el sobre esfuerzo de la electronica.

title: Memo Dispenser for a magnetic Bulletboard cnc/laser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
As one of my first creations with my cnc I tried a replacement for a diy-memo-dispenser using a dovetailed construction. It can hold up to four pens and a lot of small slips of paper. The dispenser is designed to be used on a bulletboard thus I inserted two neodymium-magnets in the back panel.

After a year of usage I revised it with a lower back (using less material) and painted it black so that the marks of pens and pencils are less obvious.

This build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 4 mm poplar plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. I used some spray-paint and sanded it.

A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to rebuild the design. In this case the nesting could be even closer. In my case I optimized the layout for my machine width of 30 cm.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more designs.
Based on my rough sketches I used Illustrator to draw the design. After 3 iterations I had a working design. Using SketchUp I validated my design.

Purpose:

This plastic part is a cover for your 200W PSU bloc.
It was designed based on model S-200-12

We are now switching our Heatbeds to 220V versions.
For Scalar M (bed 300x220mm) => 400W 220V heatbed , can heat to 110°C in 2 minutes
For Scalar XL (bed 435x320mm) => 700W 220V Heatbed, can heat to 110°C in 3 minutes
Doing this allows us to reduce the power needed on the Power supply side.
We can now use 200W PSU instead of 360W PSU.
200W still allows us to provide enough power for 2 extruders + 2 hotends and still keep enough flexibility for extensions.

PSU outside dimensions:
200x110x50mm

Updates:

  • 2017.09.10: added box for 200W with 3 outputs
  • 2016.07.14 - Top Holder Added: Support_Chassis_Top_200W.stl

Plastic Parts

We provided

  • The PSU Box : BOX_PSU_200w_12V
  • The PSU mockup : PSU_200W_12V
  • The Top PSU holder: Support_Chassis_Top_200W

CAD software to use

CAD files are provided as is and are compatible with DesignSpark Mechanical V2.0

Needed Parts

To complete this PSU Box you will need the following parts:

  • IEC 320 Connector with fuse ( http://3dmodularsystems.com/en/electronic/71-iec320-c14-power-supply-plug-with-red-light-rocket-switch-and-fuse-holder.html )
  • M3x6mm For thermoplastic
  • M3x8mm for metal
  • 5x20mm Fuse (1A)
  • 15 cm 2.5mm² Red wire (Wire inside the casing from the connector to the PSU)
  • 15 cm 2.5mm² Black wire (Wire inside the casing from the connector to the PSU)
  • 15 cm 2.5mm² Yellow/Green wire (Wire inside the casing from the connector to the PSU)
  • 2 Meters 2.5mm² Black wires (Wires from PSU to your Ramps or other electronics)

  • 2 Meters 2.5mm² Red wires (Wires from PSU to your Ramps or other electronics)

  • The metal screw will go on the side of the PSU.
  • The Thermoplastic will go at the bottom. The metal insert might not have thread, so the thermoplastic shape of the screw will allow you to attache the bottom part of the box to the PSU itself.

The 200W PSU model has very limited ways to attach the front casing. The 2 chosen screw holes seems enough to keep the casing in place.

description.text:
This is very much in progress of being built and designed ad-hoc, But I've started on a Ultimaker style bot that is a meter cubed in volume. So that I can print a Chair!
Each corner is printed on my Makerbot, and then standard 4x2 steel tubing can be inserted to make the frame.
Each side is cross braced with threaded rod to make it true and the 16mm ground shafts are used as guides for the head.
The head is on a 10mm shaft and houses two LLU10's for smooth running.
The head is designed to accept up to 4 heads but I will need to figure out a way to keep the weight down, because even with 10mm shafting there is some flexing.
The platform when build will have two ball screw on opposite corners with two linear bearings on the other corners.
Each axis will be powered by Nema23's at 48v going through some Gecko Drivers, but I intend to rig up my Makerbot Mother board to control this, so that I can re use the Extruder controller for the head.
Anyway, I will start posting files when they are ready.

title: Dial Indicator for Printrbot LC and Plus

description.text:
I know, there are more dial indicator bracket designs than there are guitar players in Nashville.  But...  
This bracket allows one to simply "clip" a dial indicator onto the parallel X-axis rods.  The bracket can slide from side to side easily.  Its Z axis repeatability has proven to be very good.  This dial happens to be calibrated in 0.001" increments, and repeatability is good to within two or three divisions.  
Knowing that people would have printers that have different rod spacing, and that the exact dimensions of holes can be tricky to set up, I have included an OpenSCAD file so that the design can be adapted.  This is courtesy of Tim Deagan on Printrbottalk.com.

I printed this in Taulman 645 nylon, with 100% infill.  I'm sure it will work with almost any plastic you care to use.  
The wedge is a small piece printed separately.  When inserted through the hole in the dial indicator bracket, it snugs everything up so there is no play or wobble.  
You may find that your dial indicator's mounting bracket is oriented at 90 degrees to the one in my pictures.  Mine was too.  It's easily fixed by removing four screws on the back of the dial indicator and rotating the back plate to the desired orientation.

description.text:
I designed this carriage primarily for the TEVO Tarantula so it can mount the Toranado 1.1 Precision Geared Extruder found at:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1246951

UPDATE: I have learned that the TEVO Tarantula doesn't use the OpenBuild V Slot rails. I am uncertain how well this will fit the TEVO rails.

This carriage could also be used on any OpenBuilds style 20X0 V-slot rail, such as a 2020, in a vertical configuration with the carriage on top of the rail or under it. So this could also be used to mount Prusa i3 accessories on a Cobblebot.

I do not have a TEVO Tarantula so I am unable to test this. However, the same wheel spacing was used on my other 2020 carriages so it should work.

This is intended to be a swap out for the stock TEVO Tarantula. It is intended to us the stock drive belt.

The screws to attach the Toranado should be round with short heads so that the screws don't interfere with the rail.

There is a very thin layer in the larger holes that can be cut or drilled out so that a bridge can be created to print the counter-sink without supports.

Use M5 screws with OpenBuilds wheels. Requires 2 eccentric spacers for the larger holes.

With the Mendelmax1.5+-style printers, you need small tools for loading filament, adjusting level and tension, etc.    This drawer includes left and right side rails and a rear panel with magnetic catch feature.   The files are mostly parametric, but the nominal is 100 mm wide and 170 mm deep, with height of 28 mm to fit between the aluminum extrusions.   
3 screws (M5)  are used to mount it.   This design clears the Y carriage plastic strap, at default dimensions, used on the linear support rail system.  It is not suitable for the older mendel 1.0 designs with 2 support rods for Y axis system.

This drawer includes left and right side rails and a rear panel with magnetic catch feature.   Two Hobby Lobby round refrigerator magnets are glued to the rear panel and a 1/2" ID steel washer is placed between them to distribute the field.  
A slot in the rear of the tray carries another 1/2" washer that is attracted to the magnets and retains the drawer.   The washer installs to the left edge and the drawer is inserted.  Use a hex key to move the washer to the center, and it will also be a drawer stop and keep things from dumping out!  
The files are mostly parametric, but the nominal is 100 mm wide and 170 mm deep, with height of 28 mm to fit between the aluminum extrusions.   SCAD source files are included with some comments for making modifications to your need.  
3 screws (M5)  are used to mount it.   One nut upper left rail, one nut lower left rail, one nut upper front crossrail.   Put in the nuts, then install the left rail.   Next is the rear panel with one M5 screw into the lower rail.   The cover is optional, but does slow filament bits from the extruder collecting in the drawer.   Cover goes into the front extrusion slot, then the rear panel is moved forward to capture it.   Slide the cover against the left rail, in the upper slot.  Insert the right rail from the front, then rotate counterclockwise into position.   Start the screw in front panel and slide it toward the Y axis idler.  
Install the tray and move the right rail to a snug slip fit on the tray.   Check that the Y axis carrier is clear, then tighten all 3 screws.  This design clears the Y carriage plastic strap, at default dimensions, used on the linear support rail system.  
Please note it is not suitable for the older mendel 1.0 designs with 2 support rods for Y axis system.    
The nut trap in the front takes an M5 half nut (thin) and an M5 cap screw can be used for a drawer pull.   A longer hex bolt or screw can be installed from the inside and a wing nut screwed on for a handle, also.  
This package does not include a full trim panel for the drawer.   With one more nut in the top front rail, a simple flat piece can be designed and printed to fill that space, if you desire.  
The STL files are suitable for ABS or PLA.  There are 2 versions of the tray included.  Tray 1 has thin 3mm tray walls and will be warp sensitive in ABS.   Tray 2 has 5mm walls and has been good for ABS prints.   The heat shield tabs should be cut away after the print is removed from the plate.   These minimize layer splitting and warping at the corners.
